  1. Question

    Consider the right triangle with lengths 20, 21, 29 and acute angles \(\phi\) and \(\theta\), where \(\theta<\phi\). Find all the trigonometric ratios.


    • \(\sin(\theta)\) = /
    • \(\cos(\theta)\) = /
    • \(\tan(\theta)\) = /
    • \(\csc(\theta)\) = /
    • \(\sec(\theta)\) = /
    • \(\cot(\theta)\) = /
    • \(\sin(\phi)\) = /
    • \(\cos(\phi)\) = /
    • \(\tan(\phi)\) = /
    • \(\csc(\phi)\) = /
    • \(\sec(\phi)\) = /
    • \(\cot(\phi)\) = /


    Solution

    This is definitional. It is also exhaustive and tediuous. Sorry?

    • \(\sin(\theta) = \frac{20}{29}\)
    • \(\cos(\theta) = \frac{21}{29}\)
    • \(\tan(\theta) = \frac{20}{21}\)
    • \(\csc(\theta) = \frac{29}{20}\)
    • \(\sec(\theta) = \frac{29}{21}\)
    • \(\cot(\theta) = \frac{21}{20}\)
    • \(\sin(\phi) = \frac{21}{29}\)
    • \(\cos(\phi) = \frac{20}{29}\)
    • \(\tan(\phi) = \frac{21}{20}\)
    • \(\csc(\phi) = \frac{29}{21}\)
    • \(\sec(\phi) = \frac{29}{20}\)
    • \(\cot(\phi) = \frac{20}{21}\)

  3. Question

    An adventurer, crossing a vast (flat) desert, approaches a distant monument. When the adventurer first notices the monument, the viewing angle (the angle of elevation to the top of the monument) is 0.55 radians.

    The adventurer walks toward the monument, getting 450 meters closer; the viewing angle increases to 1.3 radians.

    How tall is the monument (in meters)?


    (Figure not drawn to scale.)

    PLEASE ROUND YOUR ANSWER TO 2 SIGNIFICANT FIGURES.


    Solution

    Below are two methods. The first uses long decimal representations to somewhat simplify the algebra. The second method abstracts the problem further to derive a formula.

    Long decimals

    First, label some unknowns with variables.


    Write a system of equations.

    \[\tan(0.55) = \frac{h}{450+z}\]

    \[\tan(1.3) = \frac{h}{z}\]

    Evaluate decimal approximations.

    \[0.6131052 = \frac{h}{450+z}\]

    \[3.6021024 = \frac{h}{z}\]

    Isolate (solve for) \(z\) in the second equation by multiplying both sides by \(z\) and dividing both sides by 3.6021024. Remember, dividing by 3.6021024 is equivalent to multiplying by \(\frac{1}{3.6021024}\), which is equivalent to multiplying by \(0.2776156\).

    \[z ~=~ \frac{h}{3.6021024}\]

    \[z ~=~ \frac{1}{3.6021024} h\]

    \[z ~=~ 0.2776156 h\]

    Substitute \(0.2776156 h\) for \(z\) in the first equation of the system.

    \[0.6131052 = \frac{h}{450+0.2776156 h}\]

    Multiply both sides by the denominator.

    \[0.6131052\cdot \left(450+0.2776156 h\right) = h\] Distribute.

    \[275.897346+0.1702076 h= h\]

    Subtract \(0.1702076 h\) from both sides.

    \[275.897346= h-0.1702076 h\]

    Simplify the difference by combining like terms.

    \[275.897346= 0.8297924 h\]

    Divide both sides by 0.8297924.

    \[332.4896035= h\]

    Round to two significant figures.

    \[h = 330\]

    Further abstraction do derive formula

    Rewrite the problem using only variables.


    Knowns: \(x\), \(\theta\), \(\phi\)

    Unknowns: \(z\), \(h\)

    Goal: Solve for \(z\) in terms of known quantities.

    Write the system of equations.

    \[\tan(\theta) = \frac{h}{x+z}\]

    \[\tan(\phi) = \frac{h}{z}\]

    Solve second equation for \(z\).

    \[z = \frac{h}{\tan(\phi)}\]

    Substitute into first equation of system. \[\tan(\theta) = \frac{h}{x+\frac{h}{\tan(\phi)}}\]

    Multiply both sides by the denominator.

    \[\tan(\theta)x + \frac{\tan(\theta)}{\tan(\phi)}h ~=~ h\]

    Multiply by \(\tan(\phi)\) to get ride of denominators.

    \[\tan(\theta)\tan(\phi)x + \tan(\theta)h ~=~ \tan(\phi)h\]

    Subtract \(\tan(\theta)h\) from both sides.

    \[\tan(\theta)\tan(\phi)x ~=~ \tan(\phi)h - \tan(\theta)h\]

    Factor out \(h\).

    \[\tan(\theta)\tan(\phi)x ~=~ \big(\tan(\phi) - \tan(\theta)\big)h\]

    Solve for \(h\).

    \[h = \frac{\tan(\theta)\tan(\phi)x}{\tan(\phi) - \tan(\theta)}\]

    If you plug in the known values, you should be able to get \(h\).

    \[h = 332.4896035\]

    Round to 2 significant digits.

    \[h = 330\]



  4. Question

    An adventurer, crossing a vast (flat) desert, approaches a distant monument. When the adventurer first notices the monument, the viewing angle (the angle of elevation to the top of the monument) is 0.27 radians.

    The adventurer walks toward the monument, getting 460 meters closer; the viewing angle increases to 0.87 radians.

    How tall is the monument (in meters)?


    (Figure not drawn to scale.)

    PLEASE ROUND YOUR ANSWER TO 2 SIGNIFICANT FIGURES.


    Solution

    Below are two methods. The first uses long decimal representations to somewhat simplify the algebra. The second method abstracts the problem further to derive a formula.

    Long decimals

    First, label some unknowns with variables.


    Write a system of equations.

    \[\tan(0.27) = \frac{h}{460+z}\]

    \[\tan(0.87) = \frac{h}{z}\]

    Evaluate decimal approximations.

    \[0.2767581 = \frac{h}{460+z}\]

    \[1.1853249 = \frac{h}{z}\]

    Isolate (solve for) \(z\) in the second equation by multiplying both sides by \(z\) and dividing both sides by 1.1853249. Remember, dividing by 1.1853249 is equivalent to multiplying by \(\frac{1}{1.1853249}\), which is equivalent to multiplying by \(0.8436506\).

    \[z ~=~ \frac{h}{1.1853249}\]

    \[z ~=~ \frac{1}{1.1853249} h\]

    \[z ~=~ 0.8436506 h\]

    Substitute \(0.8436506 h\) for \(z\) in the first equation of the system.

    \[0.2767581 = \frac{h}{460+0.8436506 h}\]

    Multiply both sides by the denominator.

    \[0.2767581\cdot \left(460+0.8436506 h\right) = h\] Distribute.

    \[127.3087425+0.2334872 h= h\]

    Subtract \(0.2334872 h\) from both sides.

    \[127.3087425= h-0.2334872 h\]

    Simplify the difference by combining like terms.

    \[127.3087425= 0.7665128 h\]

    Divide both sides by 0.7665128.

    \[166.0882061= h\]

    Round to two significant figures.

    \[h = 170\]

    Further abstraction do derive formula

    Rewrite the problem using only variables.


    Knowns: \(x\), \(\theta\), \(\phi\)

    Unknowns: \(z\), \(h\)

    Goal: Solve for \(z\) in terms of known quantities.

    Write the system of equations.

    \[\tan(\theta) = \frac{h}{x+z}\]

    \[\tan(\phi) = \frac{h}{z}\]

    Solve second equation for \(z\).

    \[z = \frac{h}{\tan(\phi)}\]

    Substitute into first equation of system. \[\tan(\theta) = \frac{h}{x+\frac{h}{\tan(\phi)}}\]

    Multiply both sides by the denominator.

    \[\tan(\theta)x + \frac{\tan(\theta)}{\tan(\phi)}h ~=~ h\]

    Multiply by \(\tan(\phi)\) to get ride of denominators.

    \[\tan(\theta)\tan(\phi)x + \tan(\theta)h ~=~ \tan(\phi)h\]

    Subtract \(\tan(\theta)h\) from both sides.

    \[\tan(\theta)\tan(\phi)x ~=~ \tan(\phi)h - \tan(\theta)h\]

    Factor out \(h\).

    \[\tan(\theta)\tan(\phi)x ~=~ \big(\tan(\phi) - \tan(\theta)\big)h\]

    Solve for \(h\).

    \[h = \frac{\tan(\theta)\tan(\phi)x}{\tan(\phi) - \tan(\theta)}\]

    If you plug in the known values, you should be able to get \(h\).

    \[h = 166.0882061\]

    Round to 2 significant digits.

    \[h = 170\]



  5. Question

    Find \(x\). The angles are measured in radians.

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-2

    The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    It is helpful to name the two lengths that add up to \(x\).


    \[x = p+q\]

    Set up the trigonometric equations.

    \[\tan(0.56) = \frac{4.1}{p}\] \[\tan(0.81) = \frac{4.1}{q}\]

    Solve those equations. \[p = 6.5396013\] \[q = 3.90307\]

    Add the parts. \[x = 6.5396013+3.90307\] \[x = 10.4426714\]

  7. Question

    A ship sailed 5.8 miles in a direction of 31 North of East. The ship turned and sailed 6.7 miles in a direction 52 North of East.


    The ships captain suffers a terrible accident. The first officer radios for help and sets anchor, waiting for help while administering first aid.

    A helicopter, starting where the ship started, wishes to fly directly to the ship. What direction (\(\theta\) rounded to nearest degree) and distance (\(r\) rounded to nearest tenth of a mile) should the helicopter fly?


    • The direction: \(\theta =\)
    • The distance: \(r =\)


    Solution

    Start by naming some lengths (the legs of the two small triangles).


    Evaluate \(a\), \(b\), \(j\), and \(k\). Remember to set your calculator to DEGREE MODE.

    \[a ~=~ 5.8 \cos(31^\circ) ~=~ 4.9715703\] \[b ~=~ 5.8 \sin(31^\circ) ~=~ 2.9872208\] \[j ~=~ 6.7 \cos(52^\circ) ~=~ 4.1249319\] \[k ~=~ 6.7 \sin(52^\circ) ~=~ 5.279672\]

    Name the lengths of the large triangle.


    Calculate \(x\) and \(y\).

    \[x~=~4.9715703+4.1249319~=~9.0965022\] \[y~=~2.9872208+5.279672~=~8.2668929\] Calculate \(\theta\). Remember to set your calculator to DEGREE MODE.

    \[\theta ~=~ \arctan\left(\frac{8.2668929}{9.0965022}\right) ~=~ 42.2645331^\circ ~\approx~ 42^\circ\]

    Calculate \(r\) by using Pythagorean Theorem.

    \[r ~=~ \sqrt{9.0965022^2+8.2668929^2} ~=~ 12.2917806 ~\approx~ 12.3 ~\mathrm{mi}\]

    Instead of using Pythagorean Theorem, you could have used trigonometry.

    \[r ~=~ \frac{9.0965022}{\cos(42.2645331^\circ)} ~=~ \frac{8.2668929}{\sin(42.2645331^\circ)} ~=~ 12.2917806 ~\approx~ 12.3~\mathrm{mi}\]



  8. Question

    A ship sailed 6.9 miles in a direction of 18 North of East. The ship turned and sailed 7.9 miles in a direction 42 North of East.


    The ships captain suffers a terrible accident. The first officer radios for help and sets anchor, waiting for help while administering first aid.

    A helicopter, starting where the ship started, wishes to fly directly to the ship. What direction (\(\theta\) rounded to nearest degree) and distance (\(r\) rounded to nearest tenth of a mile) should the helicopter fly?


    • The direction: \(\theta =\)
    • The distance: \(r =\)


    Solution

    Start by naming some lengths (the legs of the two small triangles).


    Evaluate \(a\), \(b\), \(j\), and \(k\). Remember to set your calculator to DEGREE MODE.

    \[a ~=~ 6.9 \cos(18^\circ) ~=~ 6.56229\] \[b ~=~ 6.9 \sin(18^\circ) ~=~ 2.1322173\] \[j ~=~ 7.9 \cos(42^\circ) ~=~ 5.8708441\] \[k ~=~ 7.9 \sin(42^\circ) ~=~ 5.2861318\]

    Name the lengths of the large triangle.


    Calculate \(x\) and \(y\).

    \[x~=~6.56229+5.8708441~=~12.4331341\] \[y~=~2.1322173+5.2861318~=~7.4183491\] Calculate \(\theta\). Remember to set your calculator to DEGREE MODE.

    \[\theta ~=~ \arctan\left(\frac{7.4183491}{12.4331341}\right) ~=~ 30.8228214^\circ ~\approx~ 31^\circ\]

    Calculate \(r\) by using Pythagorean Theorem.

    \[r ~=~ \sqrt{12.4331341^2+7.4183491^2} ~=~ 14.4780774 ~\approx~ 14.5 ~\mathrm{mi}\]

    Instead of using Pythagorean Theorem, you could have used trigonometry.

    \[r ~=~ \frac{12.4331341}{\cos(30.8228214^\circ)} ~=~ \frac{7.4183491}{\sin(30.8228214^\circ)} ~=~ 14.4780774 ~\approx~ 14.5~\mathrm{mi}\]



  9. Question

    A line forms an angle of inclination of \(\theta=0.79\) radians with the horizontal axis. What is the slope of the line?


    In other words, the line could be represented with a linear equation, \(y=mx+b\), and your goal is to determine \(m\).

    The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    Draw a right triangle.


    Remember that the slope is equivalent to rise over run.

    \[m = \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}\]

    Recognize that the tangent (trigonometric) function also represents this ratio.

    \[\tan(\phi) = \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}\]

    Use the transitive property of equality.

    \[m ~=~ \tan(0.79) ~=~ 1.0092463\]

  11. Question

    On steep streets, you may see signs that indicate the grade, which is usually shown as a percentage. The grade is equivalent to slope, written as a percentage.

    The highest grade of the Ashuwillticook Rail Trail is 2.5%. The Mohawk Trail (Route 2), near the hairpin turn, has sections of 8% grade. Notch Road, heading up Mount Greylock, has grades as high as 12%. Circuit Road, below Berry Pond in Pittsfield State Forest, has a section of 16% grade. Thunderbolt Ski Trails steepest section has 35% grade.


    A grade of 31.1% implies that for every 100 feet of horizontal travel (as seen on a map), the elevation changes by 31.1 feet. We wish to determine the angle of inclination (in degrees) of a 31.1% grade.


    Find \(\theta\), the angle of inclination in degrees. The tolerance is \(\pm0.1^\circ\).


    Solution

    Remember to use DEGREE mode.

    \[\theta = \arctan\left(\frac{31.1}{100}\right)\]

    \[\theta \approx 17.3^\circ\]

    Humans tend to think terrain is much steeper than it truly is. It is tempting to think a hill is going up at a 45\(^\circ\) angle, but this would be a 100% grade, much steeper than any public street in the world. The steepest public roads have angles of inclination under \(22^\circ\) (under 40% grade). Some examples: Canton Avenue in Pennsylvania, Baldwin Street in New Zealand, and Ffordd_Pen_Llech in North Wales.



  12. Question

    On steep streets, you may see signs that indicate the grade, which is usually shown as a percentage. The grade is equivalent to slope, written as a percentage.

    The highest grade of the Ashuwillticook Rail Trail is 2.5%. The Mohawk Trail (Route 2), near the hairpin turn, has sections of 8% grade. Thunderbolt Ski Trails steepest section has 35% grade.


    A grade of 43.1% implies that for every 100 feet of horizontal travel (as seen on a map), the elevation changes by 43.1 feet. We wish to determine the angle of inclination (in degrees) of a 43.1% grade.


    Find \(\theta\), the angle of inclination in degrees. The tolerance is \(\pm0.1^\circ\).


    Solution

    Remember to use DEGREE mode.

    \[\theta = \arctan\left(\frac{43.1}{100}\right)\]

    \[\theta \approx 23.3^\circ\]

    Humans tend to think terrain is much steeper than it truly is. It is tempting to think a hill is going up at a 45\(^\circ\) angle, but this would be a 100% grade, much steeper than any public street in the world. The steepest public roads have angles of inclination under \(22^\circ\) (under 40% grade). Some examples: Canton Avenue in Pennsylvania, Baldwin Street in New Zealand, and Ffordd_Pen_Llech in North Wales.



  13. Question

    A point on a Cartesian plane is denoted in polar coordinates: \[r = 3.36\] \[\theta=\frac{20\pi}{11}\]

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-2

    Please determine the rectangular coordinates (\(x\) and \(y\)).

    • The horizontal coordinate: \(x=\)
    • The vertical coordinate: \(y=\)


    Solution

    We can use right-triangle trigonometry. Start by finding the reference angle. To do this, find the absolute difference between the angle and the nearest multiple of \(\pi\). So, in this case, the reference angle (\(\phi\)) is:

    \[\phi ~=~ \left|\frac{20\pi}{11}-2\pi\right|\]

    \[\phi ~=~ \frac{2\pi}{11}\]

    plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-4

    Remember, \(r=3.36\). Use trigonometry to calculate the lengths of the right triangle.

    \[|x| ~=~ 3.36\cos\left(\frac{2\pi}{11}\right) ~=~ 2.8266119\]

    \[|y| ~=~ 3.36\sin\left(\frac{2\pi}{11}\right) ~=~ 1.8165531\]

    Since we are in quadrant 4, we know the signs of \(x\) and \(y\).

    \[x = 2.8266119\]

    \[y = -1.8165531\]

    If you round to the hundredths place:

    \[x = 2.83\] \[y = -1.82\]

    Another approach

    It turns out that the trigonometric functions are defined for all angles (not just acute angles). The way they are defined actually makes this problem trivial. There is no need to find an acute reference angle.

    \[x = r \cos(\theta)\]

    \[y = r \sin(\theta)\]

    Using these above formulas will work directly.
